Would you Trade a Chocolate for An Apple?

Draft – November 13, 2025
By Mateo, Erik, Thomas, Siramane, Chen, Eriya

Do trade policies influence your choice of snack?

1.1. Several economies around the world are adopting a more proactive public health policy to improve nutrition and reduce non-communicable diseases, such as coronary heart disease, stroke and diabetes. As public health agencies and researchers increasingly focus on whether the processing of foods (e.g. additives, preservatives, and flavourings) negatively affects health , this note examines data on international food trade – specifically trade flows and tariffs – to explore the linkages between trade policies and the type of food traded across borders.

Two caveats are important :

  1. First, we do not suggest that trade policy is an instrument for health policy. This blog is agnostic on the policy choice of WTO Members – it is solely intended to highlight the existence of possible patterns among policy choices through an analysis of data (HS lines and tariffs).

  2. Second, nothing here should be taken to suggest that all food processing necessarily poses a risk to human health or negatively impacts the nutritional quality of food. Some processing technologies, like pasteurization and refrigeration, have played essential roles in ensuring food safety, nutritional quality, and accessibility.

From tariff lines to food processing categories

This note contributes to the growing body of work linking trade and nutrition by systematically identifying relevant food products at the tariff-line level under the Harmonized System (HS) and mapping them to the NOVA classification, which categorizes foods by degree of processing. Mapping international trade data on tariffs with the degree of food processing enables a closer examination of possible trade and nutrition linkages.

The NOVA food classification system, developed by researchers at the University of Sao Paulo (Brazil) in 2010 , categorizes foods into four groups according to their degree of processing. It has been widely applied in the scientific literature. The first three groups - (i) unprocessed or minimally processed foods; (ii) processed culinary ingredients; (iii) processed foods - are the basis of long-established dietary patterns, including those known to promote long and healthy lives. The fourth group, ultra-processed foods, typically consists of industrial formulations made largely or entirely from substances derived from foods (such as oils, fats, starches, or protein isolates) and from additives developed through processes such as hydrogenation, extrusion, or pre-frying. These foods generally contain little or no intact whole food and are often nutritionally unbalanced and liable to overconsumption. For analytical clarity, we grouped the four NOVA categories into three broad clusters as follows:

  • Unprocessed foods (NOVA Group 1) – about 60% of our basket (e.g. fresh fruits and vegetables, grains of wheat, oats and other cereals, and lentils, chickpeas and other legumes).
  • Processed foods (NOVA Groups 2 and 3) – This is a simplification of the NOVA classification for purposes of this note, whereby 'processed foods' include both culinary ingredients (e.g. oils, fat, sugar and salt) and moderately processed items (e.g. canned vegetables, cheese or bread). They represent about 32% of our basket.
  • Ultra-processed foods (NOVA Group 4) – about 8% of our basket (e.g. ice-cream, sugary drinks, packaged snacks or instant noodles).

In total, we have applied this classification to 797 tariff lines at the 6-digit level under the HS system. This covers, in our estimation, most food products that are traded. The full listing is available here.

What the Data Reveal :

From 1996 to 2024, global imports of unprocessed foods have grown more rapidly than those of processed or ultra-processed foods, both in total value and on a per capita basis. The increase in total value has been most pronounced in Asia, reflecting its scale and population growth, while per capita imports have risen most strongly in Europe, North America, and Oceania. In these three regions, per capita imports of processed and ultra-processed foods have also risen, but not as sharply. For Africa, Asia, and South and Central America and the Caribbean, the trend in per capita imports has been more stable and, in the last decade, has even shown signs of declining. This shift suggests that global trade patterns continue to be shaped by demand for primary agricultural commodities and ingredients, rather than by processed or ultra-processed food products.

The mapping shows that average MFN tariffs tend to be lower for unprocessed foods than for processed or ultra-processed foods. However, this is not universally the case. Some economies have lower tariffs on ultra-processed foods, potentially incentivizing their trade, while others have retained higher tariffs on such products. At a more granular level, most economies in the top 20 importers of all food categories impose relatively low tariffs across the three food products categories, though differences remain. For example, within the top 20 importers, some economies impose significantly higher tariffs on ultra-processed vis-à-vis unprocessed food products, whereas other economies impose significantly higher tariffs on unprocessed food products than on ultra-processed ones.

Linking trade and nutrition: takeaways and next steps

Mapping tariffs onto the NOVA framework provides a useful lens for examining how trade policies and nutrition may intersect. It shows that although MFN tariffs tend to favour unprocessed foods, the mapping does not suggest a single global pattern. Tariff structures are diverse and complex. At the same time, trade data does show a strong growth in trade in food products overall with imports of unprocessed foods expanding much faster than those of processed or ultra-processed products, both in total and per-capita terms. The findings are relevant for policymakers and researchers exploring how trade measures intersect with public health objectives and policies. Decisions on tariffs levels often have indirect implications for diet quality and public health outcomes. As discussions on trade, food systems, and public health continue domestically and at the international level, a better understanding of how trade measures relate to the types of foods traded can inform more coherent policymaking across these domains.

Although the focus here is on tariffs, non-tariff measures, such as mandatory nutrition labels, advertising restrictions, or reformulation standards , play an important role in shaping food consumption patterns. An increasing number of food-related regulations are being notified to the WTO under the WTO Agreement on Technical Barrier to Trade (TBT). Several have been raised as 'Specific Trade Concerns' in the TBT Committee. A future instalment will examine these non-tariff measures—particularly standards and regulations—to explore how they further influence the relationship between trade and nutrition.
